The interest today is 1.52% and assuming an average change of 0.07% every two days, this leaves the 1.70% mark at 2.5 sigmas, which assuming a normal distribution gives a 0.7% (rounded to 1%) probability of being reached. Of course this is a very coarse and naive model, but probably might be good enough.

In less than one month the 10-yr US Treasury yield has dropped from over 2% to a bit over 1.5%. Going back to November of 2018 the trend has been down. So with less than two weeks to go until August 31 it may seem obvious that the correct answer to this question is "less than 1.7." The problem is that a single tweet about a trade deal with China could cause a snap back in long-term interest rates, which could easily exceed 1.7%. So this has become a bet on whether or not, and when, Trump decides to call a truce with China.

Continued decline in yields due to a flight to safety. Updating despite softening of trade tensions given muted market reactions. The markets seem to be responding the “feedback loop” by keeping prices and yields low knowing that a rally will only embolden further action on China. I think this is the main reason Treasury yields are quick to fall on bad news, but slow to rally on good news. My expectation is that this dynamic will continue until a meaningful deal is reached (seems unlikely in <1 month).

Historical data suggests that each round of trade escalation and de-escalation puts downside pressure on yields with limited rebound. In other words - despite the US and China being no closer to a trade deal than they were last Spring, the 10 year yield is lower. That gives me confidence that, while yields may hold flat, a rebound seems less likely.

The way I see it, fundamentals in the equity markets are primarily driving the 10 yr yield right now. Lower rates (likely cut in july) reduce the discount applied to future earnings and earnings themselves have been moderately strong. This is creating a shift out of longer duration fixed income into equities and pushing 10 year rates higher. I think there is a ceiling however, and we are very near it.
